title: For Sale:  ASP "Quest For Excellence"
postcontent: Designed in the 1960s by Paris Theodore, the ASP takes a Smith & Wesson Model 439 and subjects it to radical modification into a dedicated concealed carry pistol. During the process the pistol is shortened, edges rounded and smooth, hammer bobbed, the triggerguard trimmed on the right side and the sights replaced with a one-piece "Guttersnipe" sighting plane. The grips are simulated black horn with transparent windows which match up with cutouts in the magazine to permit assessment of remaining ammunition. This particular ASP is part of the "Quest for Excellence" limited series, 100 pistols total with a special series marking on the left side of the slide (this one numbered "052" of the set) as well as a set of three high-visibility night sight dots integrated into the Guttersnipe plane; in conditions too dark to use the Guttersnipe, the dots generate a sight picture comparable to more conventional blade and notch night sights. A plethora of accessories are included with the pistol. First is a leather-bound book style case, titled "Quest for Excellence" by Norman, which holds the pistol, an enamel-finished "Death Watch" pin, a matching numbered holdout knife (7" OAL, 3" double edged spear point blade, skeleton grip, nicely balanced) and up to two extra magazines. title: For Sale:  Top Lever Hammer
postcontent: This top lever hammer shotgun is a Grade 2 (G) and appears to all be original. Serial number research indicates a build year  of 1887. The barrels are fine three-grade Damascus steel, 30” length, and measure to be choked Improved Cylinder. They ring true and have a light amount of bluing left on the patina finish. There are two light dings in the barrels within 8” of the muzzle. The bores show light to moderate pitting.The receiver, hammers, and dogleg top lever still have strong engraving. The side plates have light case color visible. The stock and forend are solid without cracks; original checkering is worn smooth but quite visible. There is a ½” long repaired area in the butt plate of some type of filler material. The wood does have small nicks and dings one would expect of a gun of this ilk, but nothing significant. The action locks up very tight without any hint of wiggle or loose fit. This is superb example of an honest side-by-side shotgun with character.
